      "id":"commentisfree/2013/oct/30/politics-market-smoke-light-editorial",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-30T22:48:13Z",
      "webTitle":"Politics and the market: more smoke than light | Editorial",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/30/politics-market-smoke-light-editorial",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/30/politics-market-smoke-light-editorial",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"36",
        "trailText":"<strong>Editorial: </strong>Battle over energy prices first of what may be many that pitch politicians against suppliers of essential services voters have come to mistrust",
        "headline":"Politics and the market: more smoke than light",
        "body":"<p>Politicians are feeling the pain of families suffering from what one pay-day borrower described as the problem of the money running out before the week does. Labour's latest party political broadcast might have taken its script from the <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171766_333999.pdf\" title=\"\">Office for National Statistics</a>' <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171766_333999.pdf\" title=\"\">monthly economic review</a>, published on Wednesday. Disposable income hasn't grown since 2009. What's even more revealing is the change in where the money goes. Ten years ago, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/30/household-spending-income-fuel-essentials-ons-energy\" title=\"\">essential spending</a> took just under a fifth of disposable income. Now it's more than a quarter. And while the consumer price index has risen by 30%, gas and electricity prices have soared by 120% and 190% respectively. So the share they take of household spending is up too, and for many homes – families with small children, pensioner households – it'll really matter. The recovery has a long way to go before, in Ed Miliband's telling conference metaphor, it lifts the little boats along with the yachts. And now that the pensions minister Steve Webb wants to cap pension fund fees, it's clear the intensifying political contest over energy prices is just the first of what may be many battles that pitches politicians against suppliers of essential services that voters have come to mistrust.</p><p>The danger is that in fixing one thing, another gets broken. The energy market is a good example. The impact of carbon pricing, for example, which is meant simply to ensure the polluter pays, is confused by being applied differentially to gas and electricity and between business and domestic users. Labour allowed vertical integration between energy generation and supply in the belief it could hold down prices, but instead it seems to allow the big six companies to make even more profits. The introduction of an annual competition review, details of which the energy secretary Ed Davey is due to announce in the commons on Thursday, is unlikely to make a difference without a wider reform of the market structure, something Labour now promises would follow after its price freeze. Meanwhile, there's a growing sense that the suppliers have managed to capture the debate, and make it not about their price rises but about the impact of green levies instead. And although Mr Davey promised to \"fight like a tiger\" to defend the levies, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/24/energy-bills-green-levies-taxation-nick-clegg\" title=\"\">Nick Clegg</a> suggests the same funding could come out of general taxation; that might be popular, but would sacrifice the power of levies to nudge consumers into cutting back.</p><p>The trust-busting mood of the times finds a more straightforward target in occupational pensions, where – as tough <a href=\"http://www.oft.gov.uk/OFTwork/markets-work/pensions/#.UnEuXxnsqAE\" title=\"\">Office of Fair Trading analysis</a> has confirmed – a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/mar/07/pensions-conspiracy-against-public-editorial\" title=\"\">conspiracy against the public</a> has been indulged in for far too long. Just as with energy, vertical integration between different parts of the business – saving, managing investment and annuitisation – obscures the underlying economics to the detriment of the customer. There are no environmental complications here: this is a simpler case of savers getting fleeced.</p><p>Desperate to get his semi-compulsory occupational pensions up and running without operational chaos, Mr Webb had pursued a quiet life with the industry. As recently as January, he likened the idea of capping charges to fixing <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/pensions/9821473/Minister-applies-baked-bean-test-to-pension-charges.html\" title=\"\">the price of baked beans</a>. Now, however, he has launched \"a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/30/pension-scheme-charges-cap-ministers-consultation\" title=\"\">full-frontal assault</a>\", publishing calculations showing how innocuous-sounding annual levies of 1.5% can disguise the swiping of a third of a pension pot, and he talks of imposing a comprehensive cap of 0.75% of fund. Bravo. That word \"comprehensive\" is all important: barring the financial services industry from any particular levy is merely to squeeze the balloon. As Labour's Gregg McClymont has pointed out for years, charges such as transaction costs are so hidden that not even the insurers record them. Having neglected to enforce openness, the government could now discover – as the consultants warn – that if you can't measure it, you can't manage it. Scepticism in government about the market is overdue. Part of the answer is better regulation, but that's not going to happen until we have real transparency.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421328862|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|b075ba59431fa7d5219dfc74f630ce3b2cfb3290 -->",
