      "id":"politics/2013/oct/30/david-cameron-inquiry-competition-energy-industry",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-30T14:51:16Z",
      "webTitle":"Cameron calls for immediate inquiry into competition in energy industry",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/30/david-cameron-inquiry-competition-energy-industry",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/30/david-cameron-inquiry-competition-energy-industry",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Prime minister makes proposal in Commons exchanges, during which Ed Miliband says he has gone from Rambo to Bambi",
        "headline":"Cameron calls for immediate inquiry into competition in energy industry",
        "body":"<video data-media-id=\"gu-video-421287805\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"\">\n        <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/10/30/ITNP_NF_PMQS_ENERGY_30_dv-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/10/30/ITNP_NF_PMQS_ENERGY_30_dv/ITNP_NF_PMQS_ENERGY_30_dv.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/10/30/ITNP_NF_PMQS_ENERGY_30_dv_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source>\n      </video><p>David Cameron attempted to inject some urgency into the coalition response to rising energy prices on Wednesday, telling MPs he wanted an immediate inquiry into competition in the energy industry.</p><p>He made his proposal in Commons exchanges with Ed Miliband that were dominated again by the issue of rising energy prices and ahead of a statement by the energy secretary, Ed Davey, on Thursday on an annual competition review in the energy industry.</p><p>This annual review is likely to be conducted by the energy regulator Ofgem, the Office of Fair Trading and the new Competition and Markets Authority, the body that will follow the current competition commission, but it is still unlikely that it will lead to a swift break up of the big six energy firms.</p><p>It had been throught the tripartite energy review could not begin until next year, but Cameron's remarks suggest the timetable will be swifter.</p><p>Cameron in the short term is going to focus on the need to shift some of the green levies to general taxation in the autumn statement, seeing this as the best way to produce a short-term reduction in energy bills.</p><p>In the exchanges Miliband claimed Cameron had gone from Rambo to Bambi in just four years and become the unofficial spokesman for the energy companies.</p><p>He said Cameron had once spoken of tough action to make sure household bills fell when wholesale prices dropped.</p><p>But he claimed the so-called big six should now be called the big seven because Cameron backed them.</p><p>Miliband said: \"Most energy companies don't want a price freeze. Most consumers do – that's why energy companies are against a price freeze.</p><p>\"You're so on the side the energy companies, we should call them the big seven – the prime minister and the big six energy companies.</p><p>\"In opposition, you said there was a problem in the relationship between wholesale and retail prices and you went on to say the first thing you've got to do is give the regulator the teeth to order those reductions are made. And that is what we would do.</p><p>\"Why, when it comes to the energy companies, has it gone from Rambo to Bambi in four short years?\"</p><p>He also asked: \"Can you explain why when wholesale prices have hardly moved since a year ago, retail prices are rising by about 10%?\"</p><p>Cameron said Miliband had been responsible for changing the competition market in energy with the result that the number of firms had fallen from 20 to 6. He also challenged Labour for voting in the Lords in favour of a decarbonisation target for the energy industry, something that is likely to lead to an increase in prices. \"If you want a price freeze, why have you just voted for a price rise?\" Cameron asked.</p><p>In the noisy exchanges on an issue that has caused Cameron difficulties for nearly six weeks, the prime minister said: \"What we need in the energy market is more competition and lower levies and charges to drive profits and prices down.\"</p><p>He also claimed Miliband had switched his own energy supply to a firm that opposed Labour's proposed 20-month price freeze.</p><p>He rebutted: \"Because we need competition and rolling back the cost of charges. Switching is part of competition.\"</p><p>Miliband pointed out that as recently as January the prime minister had been promoting a green levy that was the \"bigger the better\".</p><p>And he said: \"On competition, here's the problem. You want a review on energy policy but that's exactly what the energy companies want. A long inquiry, kicking the problem into the long grass.</p><p>\"How will a review that reports next summer help people to pay their bills this winter?\"</p><p>Cameron replied: \"We want a competition inquiry that starts straight away.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421295751|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|5c01ad7efc7b5b1734bafa1edaa23bea280fc591 -->",
