      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Energy secretary says government will pressure big six firms, who are 'clearly making too much from some consumers'",
        "headline":"Ed Davey: easier switching between energy firms will fight fuel poverty",
        "body":"<p>The energy secretary, Ed Davey, has promised to make switching between utilities companies easier and quicker as he expressed concern that only \"the internet-savvy\" were taking advantage of cheap deals.</p><p>He also promised an annual check on competitiveness will make it easier for smaller firms to sell in the wholesale electricity market.</p><p>Four of the six energy firms have announced price rises of 9%, and ministers are also looking in the autumn statement at how some green or social levies can be shifted to general taxation or reduced.</p><p>Davey, speaking on the BBC, said easier switching could help people save up to £400 a year.</p><p>Davey's aides says the measures will make it easier for customers to switch energy suppliers within 24 hours, rather than the five weeks it currently takes.</p><p>He said some of the big six firms \"are clearly making too much from some of their consumers because that is how they make so much money\", and that \"some of the companies try to lock in their customers by making it difficult to switch\".</p><p>He claimed he had personally saved £240 by switching, saying: \"The big six have basically been making it difficult to switch. That's not acceptable. It won't necessarily come down to 24 hours for everyone straight away. This is going to take some time to deliver.\"</p><p>In banking, the average switch time was five days, he said.</p><p>He promised the government \"will be on the backs of the big six until they ensure customers can switch and get the best deals that the market is providing\".</p><p>He said he was worried that it was \"the internet-savvy or the smartphone generation that were getting the best deals. I want markets to help the fuel-poor.\"</p><p>He added he hoped the Big Energy Saving Network – volunteer community activists meeting energy customers face to face – would be trained up to help the most vulnerable on how to reduce their bills, or switch.</p><p>He said he had already changed the electricity wholesale market so independent generators can trade and sell in that market alongside the big six companies.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421352034|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|b5865ec18a08f30c479b04c456ffa3df82b43115 -->",
