      "id":"politics/2013/oct/31/energy-secretary-criminal-sanctions-market-manipulation",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-31T19:36:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Energy secretary considers criminal sanctions for market manipulation",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/31/energy-secretary-criminal-sanctions-market-manipulation",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/31/energy-secretary-criminal-sanctions-market-manipulation",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"15",
        "trailText":"<p>Ed Davey unveils reforms including moves to enable consumers to switch in 24 hours and an annual review of competition</p>",
        "headline":"Energy secretary considers criminal sanctions for market manipulation",
        "body":"<p>The government  has set out a wave of reforms for the energy industry including the prospect of criminal sanctions for market manipulation, an Ofgem investigation into companies' profits, and moves to make it possible for consumers to switch suppliers within 24 hours.</p><p>Giving the annual energy statement to MPs on Thursday, the energy secretary, Ed Davey, said: \"The public need to know our reforms will have teeth, that companies that play outside the rules will be penalised and fined.\"</p><p>But the announcements in the Commons were immediately derided by shadow energy secretary Caroline Flint, who said they would let the big energy firms off the hook, and claimed that the government had repeatedly announced reviews of the market that led to nothing.</p><p>Davey said he would \"consult on the introduction of criminal sanctions for anyone found manipulating energy markets and harming the consumer interest\".</p><p>Energy department officials argued it was not clear that existing criminal sanctions on market manipulation applied to the energy industry. Sanctions might  include a jail sentence of as long as seven years.</p><p>Paul Massara, chief executive of RWE npower, one of the \"big six\" energy firms, tweeted in angry response: \"Lots of wild talk about cartels but no evidence and the facts don't support. Where is the evidence? Put up or shut up.\"</p><p>Only four months ago Davey announced that Ofgem, the energy regulator had been given new powers to demand access to information, inspect premises and impose unlimited fines for those who break the law.</p><p>Davey also said that he expected Ofgem to provide a full report by the spring on the financial transparency of the energy companies and ways it could be improved.  Ofgem's own data suggests wholesale prices were almost flat over the past year, rising by just 1.7%.  But the energy companies have criticised Ofgem's approach, saying its method of measuring does not reflect the way they buy gas and electricity.&nbsp;</p><p>Ofgem has repeatedly said it believes the energy firms' profits are broadly transparent, but a fortnight ago conceded to the energy select committee that a further review was worthwhile. Critics claim it is not possible to work out what prices energy generation companies are charging to their retail arms in the wholesale market.</p><p>Davey said there would be an annual review of competition in the market.</p><p>Davey also wants energy firms to allow customers to switch providers more quickly than the current average of five weeks,  which includes a statutory two-week cooling off period before the process of switching can start. The industry says the two-week cooling off period is intended to protect consumers.</p><p>It is estimated that 3 million customers switch each year and firms such as First Utility has said it should be possible to offer a target of 24-hour switching, something Davey would like all firms to match.</p><p>It has been alleged that energy firms overcharge customers that are unlikely to move and offer far cheaper rates to those liable to switch.</p><p>Davey said he feared only \"the smartphone generation and the internet-savvy\" knew how to switch, adding: \"We want to push energy companies to make switching quicker and easier because consumer action can force suppliers to change their ways.\"</p><p>He added that bills were being redesigned to give people the information they needed to make switching easy.</p><p>Davey also announced that his department would work with the Post Office to signpost elderly and vulnerable people to the 500 volunteers being trained by the Big Energy Saving Network to help people find ways to cut their bills.</p><p>In her response to Davey, Flint said: \"Let me ask you how is it possible that social and environmental obligations, which on your own department's figures only make up £113 of people's bills, can account for price rises of £400?\"</p><p>She also pointed out: \"There have been 17 investigations into the energy markets since 2001. If you are today announcing the launch of a new annual review of competition in the energy markets, what on earth has Ofgem been doing all this time? And what do you expect them to find out in the next 10 months which they haven't discovered in the last 10 years?</p><p>\"The last review by Ofgem, which you gave your full backing to, only finished in June,\" she added.</p><p>Angela Knight, chief executive of Energy UK, the industry body, said the timetable for switching was partly laid down in law. \"Switching quickly, yes, it can be done, and there's certainly a lot of work that's under way and we can bring forward some of those changes pretty quickly,\" she said.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421383916|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|5ec19f44d9637e35fa98396579bde8c0968c5698 -->",
