        "newspaperPageNumber":"4",
        "trailText":"<p>Figures seen by the Guardian show that 3.7 million npower customers were owed an average of £106.89 each in May 2012</p>",
        "headline":"Energy bills: npower amassed £400m credit from customers",
        "body":"<p>The row over high energy bills was stoked on Sunday, with new figures seen by the Guardian showing that npower, one of the big six suppliers, owed its customers almost £400m at one stage last year.</p><p>The latest controversy around overcharging comes as Sam Laidlaw, the boss of Centrica and the most senior executive in the energy supply sector, breaks his silence to admit at the CBI conference on Monday that public trust in his industry has broken down.</p><p>Npower, which is owned by the German generator RWE, claimed the £400m had been created largely through the direct debit system as householders built up a balance ahead of higher winter fuel consumption.</p><p>But Caroline Flint MP, the shadow energy and climate change secretary, said energy prices were high enough without people being charged for gas and electricity they were yet to use.</p><p>\"It is one thing for energy companies to spread the costs of energy evenly throughout winter and summer, but quite another to have millions of customers in credit for the whole year. Energy companies must put an end to this overcharging,\" she said.</p><p>The npower figures, from May 2012, show that 3.7 million customers were owed an average of £106.89 each, while 1.8 million householders owed the company an average of £82.56.</p><p>This means that npower held £395m of customers' money while being owed around £145m, during a period when only 65% of the company's customer base used direct debits to pay their bills.</p><p>The sums involved would have enabled npower to earn substantial amounts of interest, but the company said the practice benefited everyone.</p><p>\"Paying by direct debit allows customers to smooth out the cost of energy over the year, meaning they often build up credit in summer when energy usage is typically lower,\" it said in a statement.</p><p>Npower said that direct debit assessments are undertaken annually and any credit balances above £60 are automatically refunded by direct credit within five days of bills being issued.</p><p>The company pointed out that householders who are still owed money by npower could ask for the balance to be paid back into their bank accounts.</p><p>Npower, which has fewer customers that British Gas or SSE, said it would need time to come up with a more up-to-date calculation on how much it owed customers and vice versa.</p><p>Similar figures for rival power firms are unclear, but a whistleblower from inside British Gas <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/26/british-gas-caroline-flint-credit-windfall\" title=\"\">told the Observer last week that the Centrica subsidiary has amassed a £20m \"credit balance\"</a> in the last financial year's accounts from customers who were in credit but had left their premises or were otherwise uncontactable.</p><p>As controversy over rising fuel costs continue, there is speculation that George Osborne will try to cut £75 a year from bills by switching various green charges into general taxation.</p><p>The chancellor is expected to use the autumn statement on 4 December to unveil plans to transfer the so-called ECO payments to insulate homes from householder to taxpayer.</p><p>Energy companies have been campaigning for this ever since the row over bills became a major political issue when <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/24/ed-miliband-labour-freeze-prices-2017\" title=\"\">Ed Miliband promised to implement a 20-month price freeze</a> if Labour is elected in 2015.</p><p>Centrica is convinced that such a move, while popular among customers, would make its own business unviable.</p><p>Laidlaw, however, will give a conciliatory speech to the CBI in which he will acknowledge public disquiet about the energy industry and accept it must concentrate on action rather than words to rebuild trust.</p><p>This contrasts with the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/24/energy-firms-declare-war-ed-miliband-fuel-freeze\" title=\"\">aggressive reaction from the industry</a> when Miliband first unveiled his proposal for a price freeze at the Labour party conference, when some senior energy industry figures warned that the lights would go out.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421568587|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|1802688d9d950dcd93fdbaa8afd971096862da04 -->",
